HOUSE BILL 627
F1 6lr0936
HB 875/25 – W&M
By: Delegates Acevero, Alston, Amprey, Fair, Fennell, Hornberger, Lewis,
Martinez, Mireku–North, Roberson, Ruff, Simmons, Taylor, Terrasa,
Turner, Woods, Woorman, and Young Young, Ebersole, and Wilkins
Introduced and read first time: January 30, 2026
Assigned to: Ways and Means
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted with floor amendments
Read second time: March 15, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Commission on History, Culture, and Civics Historic, Cultural, and Civic
3 Contributions in Education – Establishment
4 FOR the purpose of establishing the Commission on History, Culture, and Civics Historic,
5 Cultural, and Civic Contributions in Education to study and make recommendations
6 to the State Board of Education and the State Department of Education to further
7 the discovery, interpretation, and learning of the history, culture, and civics of the
8 United States and Maryland and to provide equitable learning outcomes consistent
9 with certain provisions of the Blueprint for Maryland’s Future Maryland Higher
10 Education Commission about certain lessons currently taught in public schools;
11 requiring the Commission to study school calendars and make recommendations to
12 the State Board and the General Assembly; requiring the State Board to identify
13 existing courses and materials to be updated into professional development courses
14 under certain circumstances; and generally relating to the Commission on History,
15 Culture, and Civics Historic, Cultural, and Civic Contributions in Education.
16 BY adding to
17 Article – Education
18 Section 7–137 24–1401 through 24–1405 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 14.
19 Commission on Historic, Cultural, and Civic Contributions in Education”
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
21 (2025 2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0627*

2 HOUSE BILL 627
1 Preamble
2 WHEREAS, The State of Maryland was identified as the fourth most diverse state
3 in the union in the 2020 U.S. Census; and
4 WHEREAS, The State of Maryland is enriched by a diverse population whose
5 histories, cultures, and contributions have shaped our communities, institutions, and
6 shared identity; and
7 WHEREAS, An inclusive and comprehensive education is essential to preparing
8 students to thrive in a diverse and interconnected society; and
9 WHEREAS, A well–rounded curriculum that meaningfully reflects diverse histories,
10 perspectives, and contributions is essential to the goals of the Blueprint for Maryland’s
11 Future, which seeks to provide equitable learning outcomes regardless of a student’s
12 familial income, race, ethnicity, disability status, or other individual characteristics; and
13 WHEREAS, The study of history and social contributions should reflect the full
14 breadth of experiences and perspectives that have influenced our State and nation,
15 including those of communities that have been historically underrepresented or
16 marginalized; and
17 WHEREAS, Providing students with access to diverse narratives fosters critical
18 thinking, cultural awareness, empathy, and a more accurate understanding of our
19 collective past; now, therefore,
20 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
21 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
22 Article – Education
23 7–137.
24 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “COMMISSION” MEANS THE COMMISSION ON
25 HISTORY, CULTURE, AND CIVICS IN EDUCATION.
26 (B) (1) THERE IS A COMMISSION ON HISTORY, CULTURE, AND CIVICS IN
27 EDUCATION.
28 (2) THE PURPOSE OF THE COMMISSION IS TO:
29 (I) MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE STATE BOARD AND THE
30 DEPARTMENT TO FURTHER THE DISCOVERY, INTERPRETATION, AND LEARNING OF
31 THE HISTORY, CULTURE, AND CIVICS OF THE UNITED STATES AND MARYLAND; AND

HOUSE BILL 627 3
1 (II) PROVIDE EQUITABLE LEARNING OUTCOMES REGARDLESS
2 OF A STUDENT’S FAMILY INCOME, RACE, ETHNICITY, DISABILITY, OR OTHER
3 CHARACTERISTICS CONSISTENT WITH THE PROVISIONS OF THE BLUEPRINT FOR
4 MARYLAND’S FUTURE IN § 1–303 OF THIS ARTICLE.
5 (C) (1) THE COMMISSION CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS
6 APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR FROM A LIST OF NOMINEES:
7 (I) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING MARYLAND’S INDIGENOUS
8 AMERICAN TRIBES, WHICH INCLUDE THE LENAPE, NANTICOKE, PISCATAWAY,
9 CONOY, POWHATAN, ACCOHANNOCK, SHAWNEE, SUSQUEHANNOCK, TUTELO, AND
10 SAPONI TRIBES, NOMINATED BY THE MARYLAND COMMISSION ON INDIAN AFFAIRS;
11 (II) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE MARYLAND
12 LGBTQIA+ COMMUNITY, ONE OF WHOM IDENTIFIES AS TRANSGENDER,
13 NOMINATED BY THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE LGBTQIA+ CAUCUS;
14 (III) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE MARYLAND DISABLED
15 COMMUNITY, NOMINATED BY THE SECRETARY OF DISABILITIES;
16 (IV) TWO MEMBERS WHO ARE TEACHERS OR HOLD A TEACHING
17 LICENSE IN THE STATE:
18 1. ONE OF WHOM IS NOMINATED BY THE BALTIMORE
19 TEACHER’S UNION; AND
20 2. ONE OF WHOM IS NOMINATED BY THE MARYLAND
21 STATE EDUCATION ASSOCIATION;
22 (V) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE MARYLAND LATINO
23 COMMUNITY, NOMINATED BY THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE LATINO CAUCUS;
24 (VI) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE MARYLAND AFRICAN
25 AMERICAN COMMUNITY, NOMINATED BY THE LEGISLATIVE BLACK CAUCUS OF
26 MARYLAND;
27 (VII) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE MARYLAND ASIAN
28 AMERICAN AND PACIFIC ISLANDER COMMUNITY, NOMINATED BY THE MARYLAND
29 LEGISLATIVE ASIAN–AMERICAN AND PACIFIC–ISLANDER CAUCUS;
30 (VIII) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, TWO
31 MEMBERS REPRESENTING HIGHER EDUCATION:

4 HOUSE BILL 627
1 1. ONE OF WHOM IS NOMINATED BY THE CHANCELLOR
2 OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM OF MARYLAND; AND
3 2. ONE OF WHOM IS NOMINATED BY THE PRESIDENT OF
4 THE MARYLAND ASSOCIATION OF COMMUNITY COLLEGES; AND
5 (IX) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT OF SCHOOLS, OR THE STATE
6 SUPERINTENDENT’S DESIGNEE.
7 (2) THE INDIVIDUALS CONSIDERED FOR NOMINATION BY THE
8 CHANCELLOR OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM OF MARYLAND UNDER PARAGRAPH
9 (1)(VIII)1 OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE INDIVIDUALS WHO REPRESENT
10 HISTORICALLY BLACK COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES IN THE STATE.
11 (D) (1) TO THE EXTENT PRACTICABLE, THE MEMBERSHIP OF THE
12 COMMISSION SHALL REFLECT THE GENDER, RACIAL, ETHNIC, AND GEOGRAPHIC
13 DIVERSITY OF THE STATE.
14 (2) A MAJORITY OF THE MEMBERS OF THE COMMISSION SHALL HAVE
15 CLASSROOM EXPERIENCE OR EXPERIENCE IN DEVELOPING EDUCATIONAL CONTENT
16 STANDARDS.
17 (E) (1) THE TERM OF A MEMBER IS 4 YEARS.
18 (2) THE TERMS OF MEMBERS ARE STAGGERED AS REQUIRED BY THE
19 TERMS PROVIDED FOR MEMBERS OF THE COMMISSION ON JULY 1, 2026.
20 (F) THE COMMISSION MEMBERS SHALL ELECT A CHAIR FROM AMONG THE
21 MEMBERS.
22 (G) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE STAFF FOR THE COMMISSION.
23 (H) A MEMBER OF THE COMMISSION:
24 (1) MAY NOT RECEIVE COMPENSATION AS A MEMBER OF THE
25 COMMISSION; BUT
26 (2) IS ENTITLED TO REIMBURSEMENT FOR EXPENSES UNDER THE
27 STANDARD STATE TRAVEL REGULATIONS, AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE BUDGET.
28 (I) THE COMMISSION SHALL:

HOUSE BILL 627 5
1 (1) EXAMINE THE HISTORY, CULTURE, AND CIVICS OF THE UNITED
2 STATES AND MARYLAND, INCLUDING:
3 (I) THE CONTRIBUTIONS OF NATIVE AMERICANS, LATINOS,
4 AFRICAN AMERICANS, AND ASIAN AMERICANS;
5 (II) THE CONTRIBUTIONS OF LESBIAN, GAY, BISEXUAL,
6 TRANSGENDER, AND QUEER INDIVIDUALS WITHIN THE MINORITY GROUPS;
7 (III) THE INTERSECTIONALITY OF SIGNIFICANT SOCIAL AND
8 CULTURAL FEATURES WITHIN THE MINORITY COMMUNITIES;
9 (IV) THE CONTRIBUTIONS AND PERSECUTION OF RELIGIOUS
10 MINORITIES;
11 (V) THE CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE MARYLAND DISABLED
12 COMMUNITY; AND
13 (VI) THE CONTRIBUTIONS OF WOMEN;
14 (2) MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE STATE BOARD REGARDING
15 THE ADOPTION OF STANDARDS AND PROGRAMS THAT ACCURATELY REFLECT THE
16 DISCOVERY, INTERPRETATION, AND LEARNING OF THE HISTORY, CULTURE, AND
17 CIVICS OF THE UNITED STATES AND MARYLAND;
18 (3) MAKE ALL ACTIVITIES AND MATERIALS OF THE COMMISSION
19 AVAILABLE ON THE DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE, INCLUDING:
20 (I) LIVE AND ARCHIVED VIDEO STREAMING OF EACH
21 COMMISSION MEETING;
22 (II) MEETING AGENDAS, MATERIALS, AND NOTES; AND
23 (III) COMMISSION REPORTS; AND
24 (4) USE MULTIPLE COMMUNICATIONS METHODS TO PROVIDE
25 UPDATES AND ANNOUNCEMENTS RELATED TO THE COMMISSION.
26 (J) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 30 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2026, THE
27 COMMISSION SHALL REPORT ITS FINDINGS AND RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE STATE
28 BOARD, THE GOVERNOR, AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
29 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.

6 HOUSE BILL 627
1 (K) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1 EACH YEAR, THE STATE BOARD SHALL:
2 (1) REVIEW THE COMMISSION’S FINDINGS AND RECOMMENDATIONS;
3 AND
4 (2) MAKE ANY APPROPRIATE CHANGES TO THE EDUCATIONAL
5 STANDARDS FOR PREKINDERGARTEN THROUGH GRADE 12.
6 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the terms of the initial
7 members of the Commission on History, Culture, and Civics in Education shall expire as
8 follows:
9 (1) the eight members representing the indigenous American tribes,
10 Maryland Latino community, African American community, and Asian American and
11 Pacific Islander community in 2028; and
12 (2) the eight members representing the LGBTQIA+ community, disabled
13 community, teachers, and higher education in 2030.
14 SUBTITLE 14. COMMISSION ON HISTORIC, CULTURAL, AND CIVIC CONTRIBUTIONS
15 IN EDUCATION.
16 24–1401.
17 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “COMMISSION” MEANS THE COMMISSION ON HISTORIC,
18 CULTURAL, AND CIVIC CONTRIBUTIONS IN EDUCATION.
19 24–1402.
20 THERE IS A COMMISSION ON HISTORIC, CULTURAL, AND CIVIC
21 CONTRIBUTIONS IN EDUCATION.
22 24–1403.
23 THE PURPOSE OF THE COMMISSION IS TO ASSIST THE STATE’S PUBLIC
24 SCHOOLS WITH:
25 (1) PROVIDING STUDENTS AN ACCURATE EDUCATION ON THE
26 HISTORIC ROLES PLAYED BY DIVERSE PEOPLE THROUGHOUT THE STATE’S AND THE
27 NATION’S PAST; AND
28 (2) REMAINING RESPONSIVE TO THE EVOLVING NEEDS OF STUDENTS
29 AND THEIR FAMILIES.
30 24–1404.

HOUSE BILL 627 7
1 (A) THE COMMISSION CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS, JOINTLY
2 APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE AND THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE:
3 (1) NINE MEMBERS, EACH OF WHOM IS AN EXPERT IN ACCURATE
4 INSTRUCTION, EDUCATION, AND CURRICULAR CONTENT IN ONE OF THE FOLLOWING
5 SUBJECTS:
6 (I) AFRICAN AMERICAN HISTORY AND CULTURE;
7 (II) ASIAN AMERICAN AND PACIFIC ISLANDER HISTORY AND
8 CULTURE;
9 (III) HISPANIC AND LATINO AMERICAN HISTORY AND CULTURE;
10 (IV) THE HISTORY AND CULTURE OF MARYLAND’S INDIGENOUS
11 PEOPLE AND THEIR DESCENDANTS;
12 (V) THE HISTORY AND CONTRIBUTIONS OF IMMIGRANTS;
13 (VI) JEWISH AMERICAN HISTORY AND CULTURE;
14 (VII) LGBTQ+ AMERICAN HISTORY AND CULTURE;
15 (VIII) MUSLIM AMERICAN HISTORY AND CULTURE; AND
16 (IX) THE HISTORY AND CONTRIBUTIONS OF WOMEN;
17 (2) SEVEN COMMUNITY MEMBERS, EACH RECOMMENDED BY ONE OF
18 THE FOLLOWING GENERAL ASSEMBLY CAUCUSES:
19 (I) THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE ASIAN–AMERICAN &
20 PACIFIC–ISLANDER CAUCUS;
21 (II) THE LEGISLATIVE BLACK CAUCUS OF MARYLAND;
22 (III) THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE JEWISH CAUCUS;
23 (IV) THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE LATINO CAUCUS;
24 (V) THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE LGBTQ+ CAUCUS;
25 (VI) THE MARYLAND LEGISLATIVE MUSLIM CAUCUS; AND
26 (VII) THE WOMEN LEGISLATORS OF MARYLAND;

8 HOUSE BILL 627
1 (3) ONE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE STATE’S DISABLED COMMUNITY,
2 RECOMMENDED BY THE SECRETARY OF DISABILITIES;
3 (4) TWO LICENSED TEACHERS, CURRENTLY TEACHING COURSES
4 THAT INVOLVE SOCIAL STUDIES OR OTHER RELATED HISTORICAL CURRICULA;
5 (4) (5) TWO STUDENTS CURRENTLY ENROLLED IN A PUBLIC HIGH
6 SCHOOL IN THE STATE;
7 (5) (6) THREE REPRESENTATIVES FROM INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER
8 EDUCATION, SELECTED AS FOLLOWS:
9 (I) ONE FROM AN INSTITUTION WITHIN THE UNIVERSITY
10 SYSTEM OF MARYLAND;
11 (II) ONE FROM A COMMUNITY COLLEGE IN THE STATE; AND
12 (III) ONE FROM A HISTORICALLY BLACK COLLEGE OR
13 UNIVERSITY IN THE STATE THAT IS A SEPARATE ENTITY FROM THE ENTITY
14 REPRESENTED UNDER ITEM (I) OF THIS ITEM; AND
15 (6) (7) ONE CURRENT MEMBER OF THE PROFESSIONAL
16 STANDARDS AND TEACHER EDUCATION BOARD, RECOMMENDED BY THE
17 PRESIDENT OF THE BOARD.
18 (B) TO THE EXTENT PRACTICABLE, THE MEMBERSHIP OF THE COMMISSION
19 SHALL REFLECT THE GENDER, RACIAL, ETHNIC, AND GEOGRAPHIC DIVERSITY OF
20 THE STATE.
21 (C) (1) EXCEPT FOR THE STUDENT MEMBER, THE TERM OF A MEMBER IS
22 4 YEARS.
23 (2) THE TERM OF A STUDENT MEMBER IS 1 YEAR.
24 (D) THE COMMISSION SHALL ELECT A CHAIR FROM AMONG ITS MEMBERS.
25 (E) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE STAFF FOR THE COMMISSION.
26 (F) A MEMBER OF THE COMMISSION:
27 (1) MAY NOT RECEIVE COMPENSATION AS A MEMBER OF THE
28 COMMISSION; BUT

HOUSE BILL 627 9
1 (2) IS ENTITLED TO REIMBURSEMENT FOR EXPENSES UNDER THE
2 STANDARD STATE TRAVEL REGULATIONS, AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE BUDGET.
3 24–1405.
4 (A) THE COMMISSION SHALL:
5 (1) THOROUGHLY STUDY THE COURSE TOPICS, CURRICULUM
6 STANDARDS, CURRICULUM RESOURCES, CURRICULUM UNITS, AND COURSE SYLLABI
7 CURRENTLY BEING USED TO TEACH STUDENTS IN THE STATE AND HOW THEY
8 REPRESENT THE HISTORY AND CULTURE OF DIVERSE GROUPS, INCLUDING:
9 (I) HOW THEY INCORPORATE BOTH THE SHARED AND
10 DISTINCT HISTORIES AND CULTURES ABOUT WHICH COMMISSION MEMBERS HAVE
11 EXPERTISE;
12 (II) WHETHER SOURCES PRODUCED BY MEMBERS OF A
13 COMMUNITY ARE USED IN LESSONS ABOUT THAT COMMUNITY; AND
14 (III) THE APPROXIMATE PROPORTION OF OVERALL
15 INSTRUCTIONAL TIME THAT IS DEDICATED TO THE HISTORIC, CULTURAL, AND CIVIC
16 CONTRIBUTIONS OF SPECIFIC DIVERSE GROUPS COMPARED TO OTHER TOPICS; AND
17 (2) STUDY CURRENT SCHOOL CALENDARS AND REQUIRED HOURS OF
18 INSTRUCTION AND WHETHER THEY ARE DESIGNED TO REFLECT THE TRADITIONS
19 AND CUSTOMS OF ALL MEMBERS OF A COMMUNITY.
20 (B) (1) AFTER THOROUGHLY STUDYING THE MATERIALS DESCRIBED
21 UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1) OF THIS SECTION, ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2028, AND
22 EVERY 4 YEARS THEREAFTER, THE COMMISSION SHALL MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS
23 TO:
24 (I) THE STATE BOARD TO UPDATE COURSE TOPICS,
25 CURRICULUM STANDARDS, CURRICULUM RESOURCES, CURRICULUM UNITS, AND
26 COURSE SYLLABI TO MORE ACCURATELY REFLECT, THROUGH EVIDENCE–BASED
27 FACTUAL HISTORY, THE CONTRIBUTIONS OF DIVERSE GROUPS; AND
28 (II) THE MARYLAND HIGHER EDUCATION COMMISSION TO
29 UPDATE TEACHER PREPARATION PROGRAMS TO INCLUDE INSTRUCTION ON
30 TEACHING THE ACCURATE HISTORY OF DIVERSE PEOPLE AND THEIR
31 CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE HISTORICAL, CULTURAL, AND CIVIC LIFE OF THE STATE
32 AND NATION.

10 HOUSE BILL 627
1 (2) IF THE STATE BOARD UPDATES ANY COURSE TOPICS,
2 CURRICULUM STANDARDS, CURRICULUM RESOURCES, CURRICULUM UNITS, OR
3 COURSE SYLLABI IN RESPONSE TO THE COMMISSION’S REPORT, THE STATE BOARD
4 SHALL IDENTIFY EXISTING COURSES AND MATERIALS THAT MAY BE ADAPTED INTO
5 PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT COURSES TO ASSIST EDUCATORS WITH TEACHING
6 UPDATED LESSONS.
7 (C) AFTER THOROUGHLY STUDYING SCHOOL CALENDARS AND REQUIRED
8 HOURS OF INSTRUCTION IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (A)(2) OF THIS
9 SECTION, ON OR BEFORE AUGUST 1, 2027, AND EVERY 4 YEARS THEREAFTER, THE
10 COMMISSION SHALL MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS ON POTENTIAL ADJUSTMENTS
11 THAT WOULD BETTER REFLECT THE CUSTOMS AND TRADITIONS OF ALL COMMUNITY
12 MEMBERS TO THE STATE BOARD AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE
13 STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.
14 (D) THE COMMISSION SHALL COMPLETE ANY OTHER TASKS JOINTLY
15 ASSIGNED BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE AND THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE.
16 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Commission on Historic,
17 Cultural, and Civic Contributions in Education, established under § 24–1402 of the
18 Education Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, shall report on or before December
19 1, 2029, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, on whether the
20 Commission has adequately accomplished its goals and whether the Commission should
21 continue.
22 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
23 1, 2026.
